step.name: verify_requirements
step.title: Verify System and Software Requirements
step.description:
All the following requirements must be met in order to successfully capture CPU MF Sample data.

Hardware:

The CPU Measurement Facility is available on all IBM System z10 or later machines. HIS Diagnostic Sample data can be enabled by all customers without a PE starting on z13 GA2.

Software:

Hardware Instrumentation Services is available on all z/OS releases since z/OS 1.8. Please see the recommended service below.

  • z/OS 1.12 - APARs OA36816, OA37961, OA39451
  • z/OS 1.13 - APARs OA36816, OA37961, OA39451, OA49287
  • z/OS V2R1 - APARs OA41803, OA42311
  • z/OS V2R2 - APAR OA48127
step.instructions: This information was provided for your understanding and possible further action as dictated by your site policies

step.name: id-32fc5360-f865-4b91-a0ce-9dea9bfe320d
step.title: Configure the Server to collect CPU MF Data
step.description:
Before you collect CPU Measurement Facility data on the System z, it is necessary to enable this support for the LPARs you wish to measure. If you fail to do this, you will get a message like this. "HIS026I MODIFY HIS COMMAND CANNOT BE PROCESSED.BASIC COUNTER SET IS UNAUTHORIZED".

Note: More information on the panels described in this section can be found in the System z10 PR/SM Planning Guide.

This guide can be found at: http://www.ibm.com/support/docview.wss?uid=isg209611e17c3b8d419852573f700645d4d.

step.name: configure_activated_lpars
step.title: For Activated LPARs
step.description:
For most cases, the LPAR to be measured will already be activated and running. In this case a dynamic update can be used to enable CPU Measurement Facility without disrupting the LPAR to be measured.

If the LPAR to be measured is already activated, from HMC or on the SE, select the Change LPAR Security icon. Then, for the LPAR(s) of interest, check the box for each of the following settings.

Counter Facility Security Options

  • Basic counter set authorization control
  • Crypto activity counter set authorization control
  • Extended counter set authorization control

Sampling Facility Security Options

  • Basic Sampling authorization control
  • Diagnostic Sampling authorization control

See the picture below:

Note that if you select the Diagnostic Sampling Basic Sampling will automatically be selected as well. Click the Save and Change button.

The Save and Change on the LPAR security panel will dynamically change the running system and also save the change to the activation profiles.

step.name: check_his_omvs_segment
step.title: Check RACF user and its OMVS segment authorization for the HIS sample data collection
step.description:
Check RACF user HIS and its access to OMVS

This step contains a program to help you check the RACF user and its OMVS segment authorization automatically. Please see the "Perform" tab.

The program will do the following:

Use the following command to check OMVS segment of the user HIS:

TSO Command
LISTUSER HIS OMVS

a. If the following message appears, the user HIS exists with OMVS segment. Please go to step 3.2 directtly, step 3.1.2 and step 3.1.3 will be both marked as "skipped" .

Message
USER=HIS ...
...
OMVS INFORMATION
----------------------------
UID= 00000000111
HOME= /var/his
...

Note: The UID "00000000111" and HOME "/var/his" may be different on your system.

b. If the message contains the following message, the user HIS has no authority to access OMVS. Please go to step 3.1.2.

Message
NO OMVS INFORMATION

c. If the following message appears, the user HIS doesn't exist on your system. Please jump to step 3.1.3

Message
ICH30001I UNABLE TO LOCATE USER ENTRY HIS
step.instructions: This information was provided for your understanding and possible further action as dictated by your site policies.

step.name: alter_his_omvs_segment
step.title: Alter RACF user and its OMVS segment authorization for the HIS sample data collection
step.description:
1. Alter a RACF userid for the HIS procedure to write data to the OMVS File System

Alter a RACF user HIS with home directory on OMVS file system

TSO Command
ALTER HIS OMVS(UID(123) HOME('/var/his'))

where UID(123) is the OMVS uid and /var/his is the default home directory of user HIS. You may choose other uid number and OMVS directory name.

Note: While OMVS access is required, there is no special authorization needed. Also, any directory can be used for the HOME directory.

2. Create the HOME directory in OMVS file system to store the HIS output file

TSO Command
omvs
mkdir /var/his

where /var/his will be the default directory where the HIS output file will be stored.

Note: If you plan to capture lots of sample data, this output directory for HIS data needs to be large enough.
For sample data, a directory with 1 GB for Basic sampling or 4 GB for Diagnostic sampling is recommended.

step.name: configure_zos_for_data_collection
step.title: Configure z/OS to collect CPU MF Sample Data
step.description:
1. Verify whether the HIS address space started already

Use the following command to display HIS address space:

System Console
D A,HIS

a. If the following message appears, the HIS address space is not started. Please go ahead with the remaining instructions in this step.

Message
HIS NOT FOUND

b. If the following message appears, the HIS address space is started. Please mark this step Complete by clicking "Finish" in the "Perform" tab.

Message
HIS HIS HIS NSW S A=0020 PER=NO SMC=000
PGN=N/A DMN=N/A AFF=NONE
CT=000.114S ET=00379.22
WUID=STC00713 USERID=HIS
WKL=STARTED SCL=STCLOM P=1
RGP=N/A SRVR=NO QSC=NO
ADDR SPACE ASTE=66D5C800

2. Create the HIS procedure

If you don’t have a HIS member in your PROCLIB like, SYS1.PROCLIB, copy the following procedure into the member, HIS, in your PROCLIB. This provides a method to start Hardware Instrumentation Services (HIS).

SYS1.PROCLIB(HIS)
//HIS PROC
//HIS EXEC PGM=HISINIT,REGION=0K,TIME=NOLIMIT
//CMDFILE1 DD DUMMY
//CMDFILE2 DD DUMMY
//SYSPRINT DD SYSOUT=*

3. Define the HIS-started task to RACF

To set up the HIS-started task to RACF, you need to define a profile for it to the RACF generic resource class called STARTED using the RDEFINE command.

Note: If the STARTED class is not active, RACLISTed, and GENERIC profile checking is not activated, use the RACF SETROPTS command to activate (CLASSACT), RACLIST, and GENERIC the STARTED class first before you can define a new profile to it. In most environments, this might already have been done. Therefore, you might not have to include the SETROPTS command to CLASSACT, RACLIST, and GENERIC the STARTED class. In this example, we include these SETROPTS commands for completeness. Running these commands when the STARTED class is already activated has no effect.

Example: RACF commands to define HIS-started task to RACF
//DAEMONS EXEC PGM=IKJEFT01
//SYSTSPRT DD SYSOUT=*
//SYSTSIN DD *
SETROPTS CLASSACT(STARTED)
SETROPTS RACLIST(STARTED)
SETROPTS GENERIC(STARTED)
RDEFINE STARTED HIS.* STDATA(USER(HIS) TRUSTED(YES))
SETROPTS RACLIST(STARTED) REFRESH
SETROPTS GENERIC(STARTED) REFRESH
/*
step.instructions: This information was provided for your understanding and possible further action as dictated by your site policies.

step.title: Start the HIS Address Space
step.description:
Issue the following z/OS Command to start the Hardware Instrumentation Services (HIS) Address Space. This will not start data collection, it will only bring up the HIS address space.

Use the following command to start HIS address space:

System Console
S HIS

If the following message appears, HIS address space start successfully.

Message
HIS002I HIS INITIALIZATION COMPLETE

If the correct driver is not installed on the system, the following error message will be reported upon unsuccessful completion of the z/OS start HIS Address Space Command.

Message
HIS031I REQUESTED FUNCTION IS UNSUPPORTED BY HARDWARE

step.name: Start_CPU_Measurement_Facility_Data_Collection
step.title: Start CPU Measurement Facility Data Collection
step.description:
At the appropriate time during the measurement (which should take place during specific time(s) such as Peak Hours), issue the following z/OS Command to start CPU Measurement Facility Data Collection:

For Diagnostic Sample Data collection (use this if sending data to IBM):
System Console
f his,b,tt='runid',path='/var/his/SAMPLE_YYMMDD_HHmm',ctr=(b,c,e),mas=all,buf=1024,st=d,sf=800000,dur=10

For Basic Sample Data collection (for customer use):
System Console
f his,b,tt='runid',path='/var/his/SAMPLE_YYMMDD_HHmm',ctr=(b,c,e),mas=all,buf=1024,st=b,sf=800000,dur=10

Where:

  • B tells HIS to Begin collecting the MF Data described hereafter.
  • TT allows you to specify a unique label or 'runid' to identify this measurement.
  • PATH identifies where the HIS output files will get written in the OMVS file system. If the user does not specify the PATH option, files will be written to the HIS userid’s HOME directory specified in the OMVS RACF segment.
  • CTR indicates to HIS that Counters are to be collected. If the user specifies "ALL", all available counter sets will be captured. Optionally, the user can select the counter sets of interest : "B" for the Basic counter set; "C" for the Cryptographic counter set; and/or "E" for the Extended counter set.
  • MAS or (MAPASID) indicates to HIS what address spaces should be included in the map. The "ALL" option (recommended) requests a map of all swapped in address spaces, Optionally, the MAPASID or MAPJOB option can be used to capture a map of only the address spaces of interest. If you specify MAPASID (MAS) or MAPJOB (MJOB) you will always map the Nucleus and LPA areas as well.
  • BUF identifies the number of 4K buffers for each logical processor where the Samples will be written out to during the measurement. The recommended value is 1024 for minimal overhead at the expense of more storage (1024 4K blocks per logical processor).
  • ST identifies the sample type. The possible values are Basic OR Diagnostic. Unless instructed by IBM, use ST=Basic.
  • SF is your sampling frequency. This value indicates the approximate number of samples per minute that will be collected during the measurement. The permitted frequency values are 1 to 2,400,000 (Samples/Minute). The default sampling rate is 800,000 samples per minute for 10 minutes, providing 8 million samples. On smaller machines, however, this default sampling rate will cause excessive overhead. Adjust the sampling rate and the duration to capture up to 8 Million samples without significant overhead. Please see Appendix below for instructions on how to determine the maximum recommended sampling frequency for your LPAR.
  • DUR is an optional parameter for the duration of the measurement in minutes. The default DURATION for instruction address sampling is 10 minutes. To stop data collection before the duration expires, you can explicitly end the measurement, "f his,e", or stop HIS, "stop his". The permitted range is 1 to 1,440 minutes.
    Note: If HIS is instructed to collect Samples (BASIC OR DIAGNOSTIC) and the measurement is expected to last longer than 10 minutes, the user will need to specify this parameter, since the default duration for a measurement with samples is 10 minutes. The DUR value can be set to the exact duration of the measurement or set to a time longer than the measurement interval for those cases where the user would prefer to control the ending of the data collection with the "f his,e" command.

Successful start of CPU Measurement Facility data collection is indicated by the following message:
HIS011I HIS DATA COLLECTION STARTED

Note: If any set up errors are encountered such as an option error, then, data collection can be by issuing an "f his,e" command and restarting data collection with the correct options. To recover in some cases, it may be necessary to stop HIS ("stop his") and restart HIS ("s his").

Note: For more information about collecting HIS data, please see the manual, z/OS MVS System Commands, which explains the details about using HIS commands.



Appendix

Hardware Instrumentation Services provides a default sampling rate of 800,000 samples per minute. In 10 minutes, this allows you to capture up to 8 million samples, plenty of samples for very accurate estimates of where CPU time is being consumed. However, on smaller sub-capacity machines, this high sampling rate could degrade system performance. The approach below to determine your maximum recommended sampling rate is intended to allow you to adjust the sampling frequency and duration of the measurement as needed to keep the system overhead low, while collecting enough samples to get accurate estimates of what code is consuming the most CPU time.

  1. First, determine the number of logical processors, including zAAPs and zIIPs on your LPAR. This number is important because Hardware Instrumentation Services tries to reach your requested sampling frequency across all the processors. Therefore, the sampling frequency on any individual processor should be about Requested_Sampling_Frequency / Number_of_Logical_Processors.
  2. Note that the weight of your LPAR may affect the total samples collected, but this weight is not a factor in selecting a maximum sampling frequency. The sampling frequency set for each CPU is calculated assuming that the processor will be active for the duration of the measurement. Samples are only captured when the LPAR under test is running on the CPU.
  3. Locate the Performance Capacity Index (PCI) value for a single core machine of your model using the Large System Performance Reference tables found here.
    https://www.ibm.com/servers/resourcelink/lib03060.nsf/pages/lspritrzosv2r1?opendocument
  4. Compute the maximum recommended samples per processor as follows.
    • MaxRecommendedSamplesperProcessor. = PCI * 800 samples_per_minute_per_PCI
  5. Compute the maximum recommended samples for your system as follows.
    • MaxRecommendedSamples = MaxRecommendedSamples * Number_of_Logical_Processors.
  6. For a 10 minute measurement, use a sampling frequency of 800,000 unless your MaxRecommendedSamples value is less than 800,000.
    • Sampling Frequency = MINIMUM(MaxRecommendedSamples, 800,000).

Example:

  • LPAR runs on a zBC12 2828-A04 machine
  • LPAR has 4 general CPUs and no zAAPs or zIIPs
  • The PCI value for the 2828-A01 is 50, so the maximum recommended sampling frequency is
    50 pic * 800 * 4 processors = 160,000 samples per minute
  • Therefore, the SF value used for your LPAR should not exceed 160,000
    f his,b,tt='runid',path='/var/his',ctr=(b,c,e),mas=all,buf=1024,st=b,sf=160000,dur=10

The table below has some other examples. Note that on systems for which less than 800,000 samples per minute are recommended (orange), a lower than default sampling frequency should be specified to keep overhead low.

step.name: Stop_CPU_Measurement_Facility_Data_Collection
step.title: Stop CPU Measurement Facility Data Collection
step.description:
If the measurement needs to be ended before the 10 minutes or the specified DUR= value, issue the following z/OS command to stop CPU Measurement Facility data collection:

f
System Console
f his,e

Successful stop is indicated by a message similar to the following:

Message
HIS022I HIS DATA COLLECTION IS ENDING. 464
OUTPUT FILE PREFIX: SYSHIS20080413.223225
...
(Sampling stops. Module map collection continues for a few minutes.)
...
HIS012I HIS DATA COLLECTION ENDED
(This message indicates that all data collection, including the module map, is completed.)

The file which contains the Counters will have a name whose format is similar to this.
SYSHIS20160301.143520.000.CNT

The file(s) which contain the Samples will have name(s) whose format is similar to this.
SYSHIS20160301.143520.000.SMP.01
There will be ONE of these files PER Logical PU for the LPAR.

The file which contains the module map will have a name whose format is similar to this.
SYSHIS20160301.143520.000.MAP

Note the output file names. These Unix System Services files can be found in the directory specified using the PATH option, or in the HOME directory associated with the HIS proc (the /var/his directory in our example).

These files are required to reduce and analyze the data from the measurement. It is also worth noting that there is no need to pre-allocate these files. z/OS will create the files as needed. However, make sure there is enough space in the HFS directory for the .SMP files which are created when collecting is started and are continually written to during the duration of the measurement. Also, the MAP file, written when data collection is stopped, can be large if a map of all address spaces is requested (as recommended). An HFS directory with at least 4GB of space should suffice for most sample measurements.

step.name: Compress_HIS_Directory
step.title: Compress HIS Directory
step.description:
Use the USS pax command to compress the contents of the /var/his/SAMPLE_YYMMDD_HHmm directory and merge them into a single file. Please create a different "hispaxz" file for each measurement. This step contains a shell script to automatically compress the content for you. Please go to the "Perform" tab.

Pax example:

OMVS shell environment
cd /var/his/SAMPLE_YYMMDD_HHmm
pax -wzvf company.runid1.hispaxz *
step.instructions: This information was provided for your understanding and possible further action as dictated by your site policies

template.inlineTemplate: #!/bin/sh hisPaxDir=`dirname ${instance-hispaxzFile}` if [[ -d ${instance-sourceDir} ]] && [[ -d ${hisPaxDir} ]] then cd ${instance-sourceDir} pax -wzvf ${instance-hispaxzFile} * exit 0 fi if [[ ! -d ${instance-sourceDir} ]] then echo "The input directory " ${instance-sourceDir} " does NOT exist." fi if [[ ! -d ${hisPaxDir} ]] then echo "The input directory " ${hisPaxDir} " does NOT exist." fi echo "Please enter the correct directory and re-perform the step." exit 8

step.name: FTP_to_IBM
step.title: FTP to IBM and Notify IBM Contact
step.description:
You can now FTP the compressed outputdirectly to IBM from the OMVS file system. Be sure to move the file in binary format.

FTP example:

OMVS shell environment
ftp testcase.boulder.ibm.com
...
cd toibm
cd mvs
binary
put company.runid1.hispaxz

Note: Be sure to notify your IBM contact when you have data available at testcase.boulder.ibm.com. Data will only be retained on this site for a few days. Also, please retain a copy of your data in case there are problems passing the data to IBM.

step.name: Move_Data_from_OMVS_to_TSO_Dataset
step.title: Move Data from OMVS to TSO Dataset
step.description:
If you like, you can use the TSO "oget" command to move the data from the OMVS file system to a TSO dataset.

  1. Pre-allocate the dataset with the attributes, RECFM=FB, LRECL=1024. We recommend that you set the last portion of the name to ".HISPAXZ"

    Allocation example:

    TSO ISPF option 3.2

  2. Copy the OMVS file to the TSO dataset in binary format.

    OGET example:
    TSO ISPF option 6
    oget '/var/his/company.runid1.hispaxz' 'userid.runid1.HISPAXZ' binary
step.instructions: This information was provided for your understanding and possible further action as dictated by your site policies
